data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No migration is needed.**

That said, for modern .NET you'd typically replace raw `Thread` usage with `Task` or `Parallel.ForEach`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` — the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort` — should you need it later.
